The Vasari Corridor - Firenze - Hotel Palazzo Guadagni|https://www.palazzoguadagni.com/it/the-vasari-corridor/|“Corridoio Vasariano”, was commissioned in 1565 by Grand Duke Cosimo de’ Medici to celebrate the wedding of his son Francesco I with Joanna of Austria. It took Giorgio Vasari only 5 months to complete this incredible project that links up the Pitti Palace, at that times the residence of the Medici family, with Palazzo Vecchio, the headquarter of the government. Thanks to the Corridor, the members of the Medici family were able to move freely and, unnoticed, throughout the city centre. The Corridor, a covered passageway almost a kilometre long, starts out from the West side of the Uffizi Gallery, heads towards the Arno and then, raised up by arches, follows the river as far as the Ponte Vecchio which it crosses by passing on top of the famous jewellery stores. The route of the Vasari Corridor ends  ...    of Florence.
